Summary of Kennicott Glacier Point Balance Work¶

Tristan Amaral, August 31, 2020¶

1. Introduction¶

The Kennicott Glacier in Wrangell St. Elias National Park and Preserve presents a unique opportunity to examine ablation zone mass balance and dynamics of debris covered terminal ice. The Kennicott Glacier’s lower reaches can be easily accessed via foot from the nearby town of McCarthy, and by Alaska standards, the glacier has been well monitored since 2016, with a National Park Service (NPS) managed ablation stake mass balance program, six meteorological stations located on or near the glacier, and remarkably dense LiDAR coverage over the terminal region. Previous scientific studies on the Kennicott Glacier have investigated glacier-dammed lake outburst floods (Anderson et al., 2003; 2005; Armstrong and Anderson, 2020), subglacial water pressure and ice acceleration (Bartholomaus et al., 2008; Armstrong and Anderson, 2017), and geomorphology of debris-covered ice (Anderson et al., 2015; Buri et al., in prep). With the installation of an ablation stake mass balance network on the Kennicott Glacier in 2016, sufficient observation data now exist to complete a partial Kennicott Glacier mass balance analysis. This is a timely endeavor, given the lack of existing mass balance research on Kennicott Glacier (with the exception of Loso et al., 2014), and the contribution that mass balance information may provide to the Kennicott Glacier Interpretation Plan. Here, I present preliminary work towards the goal of determining point balances at ablation stake locations on the lower Kennicott Glacier during the period 2016 to 2020. Using text and code, this document describes the input data sets, quality control steps, lapse rate calculations, and an example melt model at a single ablation stake for the Kennicott Glacier. All data files and code is stored on the Kennicott-Glacier-Sharing GitHub site.

2. Input Data¶

Below I briefly describe each meteorological data set and its usage in the analysis. I only provide details on the period of data collection relative to the 2016 – 2020 period. Data sets and associated metadata are saved in the Raw_Climate_Records while formatted data (pickle dataframes and csv files) and associated metadata are found in the DATA folder on the GitHub.

1. United States Geological Survey (USGS) Kennicott River gage station: A USGS gage site records water discharge and stage on the Kennicott River in the town of McCarthy, less than 2 miles from the outlet at the Kennicott Glacier. This site contains air temperature data recorded at 15-minute intervals. The data are continuous from 2016 to 2020, with the exception of an 7 month data gap between October 10, 2018 and May 8, 2019.

2. National Weather Service Cooperative Observation Site (referred to as NWS coop) A cooperative citizen observer conducted daily air temperature, precipitation, and weather observations from January 1, 2016 to December 31, 2017. Daily air temperature measures include daily maximum, mean, and average temperatures. This data set is not used in the lapse rate calculation due to its spatial correlation with the USGS temperature record, and the lack of recorded temperature data more recent than 2017.
In [12]:
def ftm(value, reverse=False):
    "function to convert between m and ft. Default is ft to m, but can handle reverse"
    
    new_val = value * (12 * 2.54 / 100) # ft to m
    
    if reverse:
        new_val = value * (100 / (12 * 2.54)) #m to ft
        
    return new_val

                         axis='columns',inplace=True,errors='raise')

coop = coop.astype(float,errors='raise')

  1. May Creek Bureau of Land Management (BLM)/SNOTEL site There are two meteorological stations located at the May Creek site east of McCarthy and the Kennicott Glacier. A SNOTEL site managed by the Natural Resources Conservation Service provides consistent records of snowfall, snow depth, and snow water equivalent (SWE) at hourly intervals from 2016 to 2020. Although the SNOTEL site also records air temperature, these data are not publicly available due to issues with sensor calibration and measurement bias. The BLM weather station records hourly measurements of general meteorological variables, including air temperature, relative humidity, wind speed and direction, and rainfall. Since the May Creek stations are not located right near or in the Kennicott Glacier valley, the BLM air temperature was not directly used in the lapse rate calculation, but was employed in the gap-filling regression for the USGS temperature record.

4. Pascal Buri Automated Weather Station (Buri AWS) A study led by University of Alaska Fairbanks Post-Doctoral researcher, Pascal Buri, managed the installation and maintenance of an automated weather station on the near-terminal, debris-covered region of the Kennicott Glacier during summer 2019. This station recorded a large suite of energy balance variables at 1-minute intervals, including air temperature, relative humidity, rainfall, radiation, wind speed and direction, and vapor pressure. These data are valuable in that they record on-glacier conditions and would be important for an in-depth look at lapse rates on Kennicott Glacier during summer 2019, but are not used in the ultimate lapse rate calculation as I show later.

5. Gates Glacier AWS This weather station is maintained by the Central Alaska Inventory and Monitoring Network and is perched on a nunatak above the confluence of the Kennicott Glacier’s main stem and the Gates branch. This site provides a near-continuous record of hourly precipitation and air temperature between 2016 and 2020. Given the high altitude of this station, it is used as the high station in the final lapse rate calculation with the USGS station as the low elevation site. Due to ongoing field work when data was downloaded, it was necessary to download the Gates 2016 - 2020 record in two parts. Data from 2016 - 2019 are fully QAQC-ed and were downloaded from the NPS IRMA site at the url below. The more recent data are provisional and were downloaded from the url listed below (courtesy of Ken Hill). As the most recent data are reviewed and published, this section can be expedited by performing a single download and csv read of the NPS IRMA data.

# --- plotting function 
def timesubplots(df):
    """Takes in dataframe with varying number of keys and plots each 
    temperature variable for each station (key). Assumes indexes are dates."""
    
    pd.plotting.register_matplotlib_converters()
    # get df dimensions and key names
    sites,vals = [],[]
    for key in df.keys():
        sites.append(key[0])
        vals.append(key[1])
    sites = pd.Series(sites).unique()
    vals = pd.Series(vals)
    vals = vals[vals!='TAVG'].unique()
    names = {'gates':'Gates Glacier','may':'May Creek','buri':'Buri AWS',
            'usgs': 'USGS Gage','coop': 'NWS Coop'}
    
    # plotting parameters
    fig,axs = plt.subplots(len(sites),1,sharex=True,figsize=(11,9))
    colors = ['mediumblue','indianred']
    
    # loop plotting
    for site,ax in zip(sites,axs): # for each subplot
        ax.set_title(names[site])
        for c,t in zip(colors,vals): # for each temp parameter
            ax.plot(df[site].index,df[site][t],color=c)

    # make labels
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, frameon=False)
    # hide tick and tick label of the big axes
    plt.tick_params(labelcolor='none', top='off', bottom='off', left='off', right='off')
    ax.set_xlabel('DATE', labelpad=10,size=16) # Use argument `labelpad` to move label downwards.
    ax.set_ylabel('Air Temperature (C)', labelpad=20,size=16)
    
    # legend
    lines = [Line2D([0],[0],color=colors[0],lw=3),
             Line2D([0],[0],color=colors[1],lw=3)]
    ax.legend(lines,['TMIN','TMAX'],loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
    
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.tight_layout(.1)
    plt.show()
    
# ---  Plot five met records
timesubplots(t)
Extra Meteorological Site: Lower and Upper Chinese AWS A collaborative project between Dr. Regine Hock at UAF and Chinese researchers installed two automated weather stations immediately adjacent to the Kennicott Glacier ; one station at 673 m elevation, and one at 2185 m elevation. Due to difficulties in installation, the upper weather station only provides air temperature data for summer 2019. The lower weather station has recorded air temperature and a suite of other meteorological variables at 20-minute intervals during summer 2018 and 2019. These data records are potentially valuable as they increase the density of monitoring stations on/near the Kennicott glacier, especially during the summer 2019 when the Buri AWS was operating. Additionally, the upper Chinese AWS is considerably higher in elevation than the Gates Glacier AWS and therefore is likely more representative of conditions near the highest NPS ablation stakes. Although I did not use data from either the lower or higher Chinese AWS, these data will potentially be key for later mass balance or meteorological study of the Kennicott in the future, especially once the record is extended past 2020.

3. Analysis¶

The analysis steps I performed on the air temperature data are necessary calculations and explorations that are necessary for future steps in mass balance estimation. Beginning with the temperature records from the above mentioned six weather stations adjacent to the Kennicott Glacier, I explored temperature relationships between stations, extrapolated temperatures at May Creek to gap-fill temperature values at the USGS gage site, examined calculated lapse rate across temporal scales and in correlation to meteorological variables, and created an example melt model for a single ablation stake site on the Kennicott Glacier during melt season 2019. The code used for each of these analysis steps is shown below, and is also stored in individual jupyter notebooks on the GitHub site.

3.1 Temperature Record Examinations¶

The six weather stations on and around the Kennicott Glacier provide an unusually rich suite of temperature records from which to derive an environmental lapse rate for the Kennicott Glacier. I employed investigative visualization to inform the station subset, time scale, and seasonal timing of the final lapse rate calculation.

# construct new custom AK summer index
def AK_ix(df):
    """ constructs new index for alaska summer that goes from
    May 1 to September 30. """
    
    seasons = {'summer': [4,5,6,7,8,9], # May - September
               'winter': [1,2,3,10,11,12]}
    months = {num:sea for sea in seasons.keys()
                            for num in seasons[sea]}
    # name winter according to year which it starts
    sea = pd.Series(df.index.month).map(months)+' ' + df.index.year.astype(str)
    # move winter years back
    for date,lab,i in zip(df.index.get_level_values(0),sea,np.arange(len(sea))):
        if date.month < 4: # subtract one from year..
            new = lab.split()[0]+ ' ' + str(int(lab.split()[1])-1)
            sea.iloc[i] = new
    # put back into dataframe
    seaidx = pd.Index(sea,name='SEASON')
    df = df.set_index(seaidx,append=True)
    
    return df

            summer.reset_index().pivot(index='DATE',columns='SITE',values=var).plot(

Several resolutions arise at this point in the analysis. First, only the Gates Glacier and USGS site temperature records are used going forward with the lapse rate calculations. These two stations provide good elevational coverage (spanning lower ~800 m) of the instrumented region of the Kennicott Glacier, they are within the glacier valley itself, and have continuous data from 2016 to 2020, with the exception of a missing winter at the USGS site. Secondly, given the usage of TAVG as the temperature variable in degree day modeling, and the consistency shown in TAVG temperature trends in the above plots, it makes most sense to derive the lapse rate from TAVG, as opposed to TMAX or TMIN. Thirdly, more investigation on temperature trends over varying time scales not shown here (but shown in Temperature_examination_07_20.ipynb) does not reveal a supreme time scale over which lapse rates should be calculated. The question of whether lapse rates should be derived from daily, weekly, biweekly, or monthly averaged temperatures remains inconclusive from the temperature trend examinations thus far. This is further explored in the lapse rate analysis itself.

3.2 USGS Record Gap-Filling¶

To prepare the Gates Glacier and USGS temperature records for lapse rate calculations, the USGS site records must first be gap-filled to make a continuous record spanning 2016 to 2020. This is accomplished by constructing a simple linear regression of the May Creek and USGS site wintertime temperatures that results in an equation to estimate missing USGS temperatures from the existing May Creek temperatures during winter 2018/2019. To arrive at a linear regression used to extrapolate values to the USGS station, first we must confirm several statistical assumptions: 1. Normally distributed data 2. Homogeneity of variance 3. Independent errors 4. Linear relationship between independent and dependant variables.¶
In [23]:
# --- Re-load Data
meta = pd.read_pickle(os.path.join(format_data,'temperature_meta.pickle'))
dd = pd.read_pickle(os.path.join(format_data,'daily_temperature_data.pickle'))

def temp_scat(x,y,title,labels,legend=False):
    fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9,9))
    ax.set_title(title)
    # plot data
    ax.scatter(x,y,s=8,color='steelblue')
    # plot 1 to 1 line
    ax.plot([y.min(), y.max()], [y.min(), y.max()], 'k-', lw=3,label='1 to 1 line')
    # put r^2 and regression line on plot
    mask = ~np.isnan(x) & ~np.isnan(y)
    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(x[mask],y[mask])
    r2 = r_value**2
    xo = np.linspace(x.min(),x.max(),)
    Yhat = (slope*xo) + intercept # regression y coords
    ax.plot(xo,Yhat,'--',linewidth=3,color='darkorchid',label='OLS line')
    # annotate with r2 and regression equation
    ax.annotate('$r^2$ = {:.2f}'.format(r2),(-40,-25),fontsize=14)
    ax.annotate('y = {0:.2f}(x) + {1:.2f}'.format(slope,intercept),(5,0),fontsize=12)
    # labels
    ax.axis('square')
    ax.set_xlabel(label[0])
    ax.set_ylabel(label[1])
    if legend:
        ax.legend(loc='upper left')
    # display
    fig.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
def gap_ix(df):
    """ Fill in a second index to use in extracting data"""
    seasons = {'summer': [6,7,8,9], 
               'winter_gap': [1,2,3,4,5,10,11,12]} # this can be adjusted based on distribution of values
    months = {num:sea for sea in seasons.keys()
                            for num in seasons[sea]}
    # name winter according to year which it starts
    sea = pd.Series(df.index.month).map(months)
    # put back into dataframe
    seaidx = pd.Index(sea,name='GAP')
    df = df.set_index(seaidx,append=True)
    
    return df

3.3 Lapse Rate Calculation¶

The patched USGS temperature records is then used in combination with the Gates Glacier records to calculate a lapse rate for the Kennicott Glacier during the ablation season. Methods for arriving at a lapse rate for an environmental area vary from just declaring the established environmental lapse rate of -6.5 degrees C/km when temperature records are too sparse, to multiple linear regressions of lapse rates with multiple predictor variables. A nice reference on best practices for calculating lapse rates is found in Lute and Abatzoglou, 2020. This paper recommends using few, non-redundant temperature stations, and calculating the lapse rate via simple linear regression with the strongest predictor variable. I loosely follow these recommendations in the analysis here. Above, I described in section 3.1 how the station set was trimmed from five down to two, while below I describe an attempt at constructing a linear regression equation for lapse rates on the Kennicott Glacier.
In [5]:
# ---- calculate lapse rates for summer
dtvg = pd.read_pickle(os.path.join(format_data,'daily_tavg.pickle'))
meta = pd.read_pickle(os.path.join(format_data,'temperature_meta.pickle'))

# useful functions
def lr_ix(df):
    """ put seasonal index into dataframe for use in splitting data into melt and non-melt seasons"""
    seasons = {'melt': [4,5,6,7,8,9,10], # April - November
               'non-melt': [1,2,3,11,12]}
    months = {num:sea for sea in seasons.keys()
                            for num in seasons[sea]}
    # name winter according to year which it starts
    sea = pd.Series(df.index.month).map(months)
    # put back into dataframe
    seaidx = pd.Index(sea,name='MELT')
    df = df.set_index(seaidx,append=True)
    
    return df

def lr_plot(daily,freq, drop_buri=True,plot=True):
    """ daily is the daily dataframe, freq is the frequency period to
    resample over. Also returns melt dataframe."""
    
    if freq != 'D':
        # resample
        df = daily.resample(freq).mean()
    else:
        df = daily.copy()
    # add melt season index in
    df = lr_ix(df)
    # subset just melt season out, drop index
    idx = pd.IndexSlice
    melt = df.copy()
    melt.loc[idx[:,'non-melt'],:] = np.nan # turn non-melt values to nan
    if drop_buri:
        melt = melt.drop(['buri'],axis=1) # drop buri for now
    
    melt = melt.reset_index(level=1,drop=True) # drop melt index
    # calculate lapse rate (high minus low) C per km
    melt['lapse'] = 1000 * (melt['gates'] - melt['usgs']) / (meta.el['gates'][0] - meta.el['usgs'][0])
    
    if plot:# plot
        plt.close()
        melt.lapse.plot()
    
    return melt

Here, we can see that the relationship is not actually that good (r2=0.17) and does not appear to really be linear. Some of the other statistical assumptions don't look good either. For example, although the lapse rates do look normal (not shown here), the residuals exhibit clear heteroskedasticity of variance with higher variance at lower temperatures tapering strongly to minimal variance at higher temperatures.

The bottom line that I arrived at given my time constraints was that, given the poor relationship between temperature and lapse rate, and the violation of equal variance and independence of residuals, it doesn't make much sense to scale lapse rates with Gates Glacier TAVG values, even when lapse rates are calculated over time scales varying from daily to biweekly. Instead, I feel it may be more worthwhile to investigate correlations between lapse rate and other met variables, such as wind speed, humidity, precipitation, lR, etc, if a lapse rate linear regression must be performed. For now, I assign the Kennicott Glacier ablation season lapse rate to the median lapse rate calculated from all daily lapse rates when TAVG > 0 degrees C.

3.4 Example Melt Model¶

Using a lapse rate of -4.06 C/km for the Kennicott Glacier, I then show an example calculation of an ice melt model for a single ablation stake site on the lower Kennicott for ablation season 2019. Steps are: 1. Using lapse rate, extrapolate USGS temperature record to the stake elevation and cumulative sum positive degree days 2. Calculate ice melt degree day factor 3. Extend modeled melt record to shoulder seasons 4. (not shown here) Compare precipitation record to modeled melt record to identify annual mass extrema

For situations where modeled melt using the DDF does not exactly equal the measured ice melt between spring and fall visits, it will be more accurate to add modeled shoulder season melt to the empirical summer ice melt to derive the full season melt amount.
In [19]:
# ---- Modeled + empirical ice ablation (For when DDF has some error...)
pre_visit = kl.loc[(kl_spring - pd.Timedelta(1,'D')),'cumabl'] # m of modeled ice melt before spring visit, not counting visit day
post_visit = kl.loc[end,'cumabl'] - kl.loc[kl_fall,'cumabl']# m of modeled ice melt post visit, not counting visit day
full_season = pre_visit + kl_swe + post_visit # add in empirical ice melt b/w visits
print('Full Season Melt for {0} during {1} is {2:.1f} m w.e.'.format('Kenn Lo',kl_spring.year,full_season))

Full Season Melt for Kenn Lo during 2019 is 8.9 m w.e.

4. Next Steps¶

The example melt model for Kenn Lo stake shows an example of the calculations that must be performed for all ablation stake data from 2016 to 2020 to eventually arrive at estimated dates of mass extrema. Details that must be worked out in subsequent analysis include: 1. Partition ablation at stake sites into snow melt and ice melt, and derive degree day factors for each. 2. Decide whether to use individual stake site degree day factors, or degree day factors for individual melt seasons, or some permutation of both. 3. Estimate ablation season and shoulder season precipitiation quantities for ablation stake sites 4. Combine melt model time series and estimated precipitation time series to identify mass extrema in spring and fall.
